data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3 supports `[DataRow]` for simple inline cases, and for type safety you can use `DynamicData` with **tuples** or a strongly-typed test data source.

**Simplest — use `[DataRow]`:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**For complex data — strongly-typed with tuples:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key tradeoffs:**

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Simplest, visible in attributes | Compile-time constants only |
| `DynamicData` + tuples | Type-safe, supports computed values | Slightly more ceremony |
| `DynamicData` + `object[]` | Flexible | No type safety, boxing |

Use `[DataRow]` when your values are constants. Use `DynamicData` with tuples when you need computed values or complex types — you get full type safety without the `object[]` boxing.
